{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"12915a57-bb57-4f9f-a3d7-5b7aebffc26b","content":"## Safe Area in .NET MAUI\n\n**`ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"`** — ✅ This is correct. It's a platform-specific that pads the page content to stay within the safe area. You need the namespace:\n\n```xml\nxmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\"\n```\n\n**`IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"` on a Grid** — ❌ This is **not** a standard .NET MAUI property. The tutorial may be referencing a third-party library or outdated/incorrect information.\n\n### Background image behind the safe area\n\nTo let a background image bleed into the unsafe area while keeping other content safe, use a layered approach — **don't** set `UseSafeArea` on the page, and manually pad your foreground content instead:\n\n```xml\n<ContentPage xmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\">\n    <Grid>\n        <!-- Background image fills entire screen, including notch area -->\n        <Image Source=\"background.png\" Aspect=\"AspectFill\" />\n\n        <!-- Foreground content respects safe area via padding -->\n        <Grid Padding=\"{OnPlatform iOS='0,47,0,34'}\"\n              VerticalOptions=\"Fill\">\n            <Label Text=\"Hello, safe world!\" />\n        </Grid>\n    </Grid>\n</ContentPage>\n```\n\nOr, more dynamically, apply safe area insets in code-behind using `On<iOS>().SetSafeAreaInsets()` to get the actual device insets and apply them selectively to your content container.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"dfd4f1d2-c64e-4683-883c-e849f154f757","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI safe area handling on iOS, specifically about two properties:\n\n1. `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"` - a platform-specific property for ContentPage\n2. `IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"` - a property on Grid for background images\n\nLet me check what I know about these APIs in .NET MAUI, particularly for .NET 10.\n\nIn .NET MAUI, the iOS safe area handling has evolved:\n\n1. `ios:Page.UseSafeArea` - This is a platform-specific property from Xamarin.Forms that was carried over to .NET MAUI. In .NET MAUI, it's accessed via `xmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\"` and used as `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"`.\n\n\n2. `IgnoreSafeArea` - I need to reconsider whether this is actually a standard .NET MAUI property. Looking at the available APIs, `IgnoreSafeArea` doesn't appear to be a built-in property on layouts like Grid in .NET MAUI, and it wasn't in Xamarin.Forms either.\n\nFor safe area handling in .NET MAUI, the correct approach is using `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"` with the appropriate iOS platform-specific namespace. I'm not entirely certain about the exact state of these APIs in .NET 10 specifically, but the platform-specific approach should still be the standard way to control safe area behavior. I'm realizing that `IgnoreSafeArea` isn't actually a property in .NET MAUI, so the proper way to handle background images extending into unsafe areas while keeping other content safe is through a layered approach using AbsoluteLayout or Grid with overlapping elements. For the `UseSafeArea` property, that's definitely valid and platform-specific to iOS for respecting notches and Dynamic Island.","outputTokens":1580,"requestId":"B807:3611D2:195582:212724:69FFDB42"},"id":"a37901e8-b501-487c-b62d-2dd5f9e4f6fe","timestamp":"2026-05-10T01:12:01.084Z","parentId":"6efd1d5b-c778-4a7c-8a3d-7564e8f3a5aa"}
